uhsin Ouj'''<br />{{nowrap|Grandfather of House Ouj}}<br />}}\n{{chart/end}}<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}<!--Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations.-->\n\n[[Category:History of Karbala]]\n[[Category:Arab dynasties]]\n[[Category:Iraqi families]]\n[[Category:Iraqi noble families]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al_Faiz_family"}
{"title_page": "Edean Anderson Ihlanfeldt", "text_new": "{{short description|American golfer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Edean Anderson Ihlanfeldt\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = 1930\n| birth_place = [[Helena, Montana]]\n| death_date = {{death date and given age|2020|04|27|90}}\n| death_place = [[Wenatchee, Washington]]\n| residence = [[Seattle]], Washington\n| education = [[Oregon State University]]\n| occupation = Amateur golfer, college golf coach\n| spouse = Robert Ihlanfeldt\n| sport = [[Golf]]\n}}\n'''Edean Anderson Ihlanfeldt''', pronounced ''island-felt'',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2011/9/6/208537/Senior-Women-Golfers-Arriving-in-Town.aspx |title=Senior Women Golfers Arriving in Town |last=Branton |first=B.B. |date=September 6, 2011 |work=The Chattanoogan |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (c. 1930 \u2013 April 27, 2020) was an American amateur [[golf]]er from [[Montana]], coach and founder of the [[University of Washington]] women's varsity golf team, and one of the most successful female golfers in the [[Pacific Northwest]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} She won several amateur tournaments, including the [[Canadian Women's Open]] and the [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=https://thepnga.org/wp-content/themes/abelltheme/halloffamemembers/edeanandersonihlanfeldt.html |title=Edean (Anderson) Ihlanfeldt, Inducted 1985 |publisher=Pacific Northwest Golf Association |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url=https://helenair.com/sports/edean-a-prodigy-at-any-age/article_de4c92bb-bca3-527b-bdd0-00a0db0f3ddf.html |title=Edean a prodigy at any age |last=Synness |first=Curt |date=September 8, 2004 |work=Helena Independent Record |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAnderson began training at age 13; in 1944, at age 14, she won her first out of six consecutive Montana State Women's Amateur golf championships (1944-49),<ref name=\":1\" /> with a local outlet calling her a child prodigy.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1949, Anderson moved to [[Corvallis, Oregon]] to attend [[Oregon State University]],<ref name=\":1\" /> where she joined the sorority [[Alpha Phi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://alphaphi.org/AboutUs/famousphis |title=Famous Phis |publisher=Alpha Phi |access-date=August 22, 2018}}</ref> While there, she practiced with friend and fellow golfer [[Grace DeMoss]], competing as both partners and opponents at times.<ref name=\":1\" /> Anderson would continue a streak of winning one major championship a year until 1954.  That year Anderson met her husband Robert Ihlanfeldt while playing golf. He proposed a week later, and the two were married in two months.<ref name=\":3\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19931021&slug=1727260 |title=Golf's Robert Ihlanfeldt Dies |date=October 21, 1993 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=August 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDuring the first two decades of her career after graduation, Ihlanfeldt won numerous tournaments: \"five Pacific Northwest titles, the Washington state crown four times, the Trans-Mississippi championship, and the 1952 Canadian Open crown.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1974, Ihlanfeldt brought the [[U.S. Women's Amateur]] to [[Seattle]] and founded the women's varsity golf program at the [[University of Washington]]; she accepted no salary during the time she coaching the team for the next eight years. In 1989, the University inducted her into its hall of fame.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1997, Ihlanfeldt brought the [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]] to Seattle.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIhlanfeldt died April 27, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanson |first1=Scott |title=Edean Ihlanfeldt, amateur golf star and first UW women\u2019s coach, dies at 90 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/uw-huskies/edean-ihlanfeldt-amateur-golf-star-and-first-uw-womens-coach-dies-at-90/ |website=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 29, 2020 |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Amateur wins ==\n*1944 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1945 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1946 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1947 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1948 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1949 Montana State Women's Amateur, Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1951 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1952 [[Canadian Women's Amateur]]\n*1953 Women's Trans-Mississippi Amateur\n*1961 Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1962 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur, Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1963 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur, Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1964 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1975 Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1982 [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]]\n*1986 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n*1987 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n*1988 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson Ihlanfeldt, Edean}}\n[[Category:American female golfers]]\n[[Category:Amateur golfers]]\n[[Category:Golfers from Montana]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies women's golf coaches]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Helena, Montana]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American golfer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name = Edean Anderson Ihlanfeldt\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = 1930\n| birth_place = [[Helena, Montana]]\n| death_date = {{death date and given age|2020|04|27|90}}\n| death_place = [[Wenatchee, Washington]]\n| residence = [[Seattle]], Washington\n| education = [[Oregon State University]]\n| occupation = Amateur golfer, college golf coach\n| spouse = Robert Ihlanfeldt\n| sport = [[Golf]]\n}}\n'''Edean Anderson Ihlanfeldt''', pronounced ''island-felt'',<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2011/9/6/208537/Senior-Women-Golfers-Arriving-in-Town.aspx |title=Senior Women Golfers Arriving in Town |last=Branton |first=B.B. |date=September 6, 2011 |work=The Chattanoogan |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref> (c. 1930 \u2013 April 27, 2020) was an American amateur [[golf]]er from [[Montana]], coach and founder of the [[University of Washington]] women's varsity golf team, and one of the most successful female golfers in the [[Pacific Northwest]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}} She won several amateur tournaments, including the [[Canadian Women's Open]] and the [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web |url=https://thepnga.org/wp-content/themes/abelltheme/halloffamemembers/edeanandersonihlanfeldt.html |title=Edean (Anderson) Ihlanfeldt, Inducted 1985 |publisher=Pacific Northwest Golf Association |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news |url=https://helenair.com/sports/edean-a-prodigy-at-any-age/article_de4c92bb-bca3-527b-bdd0-00a0db0f3ddf.html |title=Edean a prodigy at any age |last=Synness |first=Curt |date=September 8, 2004 |work=Helena Independent Record |access-date=August 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nAnderson began training with at age 13; in 1944, at age 14, she won her first out of six consecutive Montana State Women's Amateur golf championships (1944-49),<ref name=\":1\" /> with a local outlet calling her a child prodigy.<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1949, Anderson moved to [[Corvallis, Oregon]] to attend [[Oregon State University]],<ref name=\":1\" /> where she joined the sorority [[Alpha Phi]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=https://alphaphi.org/AboutUs/famousphis |title=Famous Phis |publisher=Alpha Phi |access-date=August 22, 2018}}</ref> While there, she practiced with friend and fellow golfer [[Grace DeMoss]], competing as both partners and opponents at times.<ref name=\":1\" /> Anderson would continue a streak of winning one major championship a year until 1954, though that year, Anderson met her husband Robert Ihlanfeldt while playing golf. He proposed a week later, and the two were married in two months.<ref name=\":3\"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19931021&slug=1727260 |title=Golf's Robert Ihlanfeldt Dies |date=October 21, 1993 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=August 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDuring the first two decades of her career after graduation, Ihlanfeldt won numerous tournaments: \"five Pacific Northwest titles, the Washington state crown four times, the Trans-Mississippi championship, and the 1952 Canadian Open crown.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1974, Ihlanfeldt brought the [[U.S. Women's Amateur]] to [[Seattle]] and founded the women's varsity golf program at the [[University of Washington]]; she accepted no salary during the time she coaching the team for the next eight years. In 1989, the University inducted her into its hall of fame.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1997, Ihlanfeldt brought the [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]] to Seattle.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIhlanfeldt died April 27, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hanson |first1=Scott |title=Edean Ihlanfeldt, amateur golf star and first UW women\u2019s coach, dies at 90 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/uw-huskies/edean-ihlanfeldt-amateur-golf-star-and-first-uw-womens-coach-dies-at-90/ |website=The Seattle Times |accessdate=April 29, 2020 |date=April 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Amateur wins ==\n*1944 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1945 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1946 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1947 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1948 Montana State Women's Amateur\n*1949 Montana State Women's Amateur, Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1951 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1952 [[Canadian Women's Amateur]]\n*1953 Women's Trans-Mississippi Amateur\n*1961 Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1962 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur, Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1963 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur, Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1964 Pacific Northwest Women's Amateur\n*1975 Washington State Women's Amateur\n*1982 [[U.S. Senior Women's Amateur]]\n*1986 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n*1987 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n*1988 Pacific Northwest Senior Women's Amateur\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson Ihlanfeldt, Edean}}\n[[Category:American female golfers]]\n[[Category:Amateur golfers]]\n[[Category:Golfers from Montana]]\n[[Category:Washington Huskies women's golf coaches]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Helena, Montana]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Albatross48", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deleted extraneous word", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edean_Anderson_Ihlanfeldt"}
{"title_page": "Scott Van Pelt", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Scott Van Pelt \n| image = Scott Van Pelt.jpg\n| caption = Van Pelt at [[Stanford Stadium]] in 2013\n| birthname =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| education = [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]]\n| occupation = [[Sports commentator|Sportscaster]] \n| years_active = 1990\u2013present\n| alias = \n| title = \n| family =\n| spouse = Stephanie (m. 2011)\n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| religion = \n| credits = Appeared on first episode of BVT ''[[SportsCenter]]'' (2001&ndash;present)<br />''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' (2009&ndash;2015, previously known as ''The Scott Van Pelt Show'') \n| agent = \n| salary = \n| URL = \n}}\n'''Scott Van Pelt''' is an American [[Sports commentator|sportscaster]] and sports [[talk show]] host. He co-anchored the 11 p.m. edition of ''[[SportsCenter]]'' on [[ESPN]], served as the co-host of ''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' alongside [[Ryen Russillo]] on [[ESPN Radio]], and hosts various [[golf]] events for the network. In June 2015, Van Pelt left his radio show to become a solo anchor for a midnight edition of ''SportsCenter''.\n\n==Early life==\nScott Van Pelt was born in [[Brookeville, Maryland]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/scott-van-pelt/bio/215846|title= Scott Van Pelt|publisher= TV Guide |accessdate= September 29, 2012}}</ref> and grew up in the [[Washington, D.C.]], area. He attended Flower Valley Elementary School in [[Rockville, Maryland]]. He graduated from [[Sherwood High School (Maryland)|Sherwood High School]] in [[Sandy Spring, Maryland]], and from the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in 1988 where he studied radio/television and film. He is a member of the [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scott Van Pelt |url=http://www.espnmediazone3.com/us/2009/11/pelt_van_scott/ |date=November 17, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Mediazone |accessdate=October 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907111744/http://www.espnmediazone3.com/us/2009/11/pelt_van_scott/ |archivedate=September 7, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nScott Van Pelt is the only good sportscenter personality, is friends with Carole Baskin, and began his career in sportscasting at [[WTTG-TV]], a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] affiliate in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1990 and then moved on to the [[Golf Channel]], where he worked from 1995 to 2000 as a studio host for some of the network's signature programs. He left the channel in 2001 to join [[ESPN]], where he serves as a presenter for ''[[SportsCenter]]'' and is one of the network's top [[golf]] correspondents, covering major tournaments such as the [[Masters Tournament]]. After acquiring the cable rights to the tournament, Van Pelt also appeared on ESPN's coverage of [[The Open Championship]]. He also is a prominent personality for [[ESPN Radio]], where he was the co-host of ''Tirico and Van Pelt'' alongside [[Mike Tirico]] before the program was canceled and replaced with Van Pelt's own three-hour program, ''The Scott Van Pelt Show'', in 2009. The show was renamed ''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' in October 2012. He is a studio presenter for the [[ESPN|ESPN Network's]] Friday night College Football on ESPN.\n\nVan Pelt has also appeared as a commentator in golf video games, alongside [[Kelly Tilghman]] on [[EA Sports]]' ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 10]]'' and ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 11]]''<ref>{{cite web | title=Van Pelt's Tiger Woods PGA Tour 10 Voice Over Session | url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=3957568 | date=March 6, 2009}}</ref> and in a comedic turn in ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force Zombie Ninja Pro-Am]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am/review/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am/a-20071108103544418012/g-20070716173729690035/p-1 | title=Aqua Teen Hunger Force: Zombie Ninja Pro-Am review | website=GamesRadar | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web | url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am-review/1900-6182650/ | title=Aqua Teen Hunger Force Zombie Ninja Pro-Am Review | website=GameSpot | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Van Pelt made the decision to stay with ESPN.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.shermanreport.com/qa-with-scott-van-pelt-looking-back-at-decision-to-stay-at-espn-radio-show-remains-key-component/ | title=Q/A with Scott Van Pelt: Looking back at decision to stay at ESPN; Radio show remains key component | first=Ed | last=Sherman | date=January 27, 2014 | publisher=EdShermanReport.com}}</ref> In May 2015, the network announced Van Pelt would leave the radio show SVP & Russillo to become a solo anchor for a midnight-edition of ''SportsCenter'', which began in late summer 2015. The midnight show covers sports events from the day, but includes additional commentary from Van Pelt and some popular elements from the radio show.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2015/05/scott-van-pelt-signs-extension-espn-will-take-midnight-et-sportscenter-solo-anchor/ | title = Scott Van Pelt Signs Extension with ESPN; Will Take Over Midnight (ET) SportsCenter as Solo Anchor | last = Livia Coelho | first = Ana | date = May 11, 2015 | work = ESPN MediaZone | access-date = May 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVan Pelt's family includes Lorenzo (grandfather)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/notthefakesvp/status/87911903053086721|title=Two Happy birthdays today: USA and my late grandpa Lorenzo from Italy via Brooklyn. I love and honor 'em both. The American dream is real|first=Scott Van|last=Pelt|date=July 4, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Cathie Mathis and Sam (parents).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.google.com/search?q=scott+van+pelt's+dad&oq=scott+van+pelt's+dad&aqs=chrome..69i57j0l3.4260j0j7&sourceid=chrome&es_sm=93&ie=UTF-8#q=scott+van+pelt+parents&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAOPgE-LUz9U3MKo0qihWQjC1JLOTrfQLUvMLclKBVFFxfp5VQWJRal5JMQA4wRBFMwAAAA | title=scott van pelt's dad - Google Search | website=www.google.com | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHis kid Charlie took a massive man size dump at age 2 during the coronavirus.\n\nVan Pelt married Stephanie in 2011 and he has two children. His daughter Lila Catherine was born in 2012 and his son Sam was born in 2016. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://playerswiki.com/scott-van-pelt | title=Scott Van Pelt Biography | website=PlayersWiki.com | accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up in Maryland and graduating from College Park, Van Pelt is a fan of the [[Maryland Terrapins]], [[Washington Redskins]], [[Washington Capitals]], [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Washington Wizards|and Washington Wizards]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://espnmediazone.com/us/bios/pelt_van_scott/ ESPN bio]\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{IMDb name|1207766}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002120649/http://sd.pikes.org/309/sd309d.html Interview with Justin Buck and George Miller (\u03c0Ka Members)]\n\n{{ESPN}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Pelt, Scott}}\n[[Category:American television sports announcers]]\n[[Category:American sports radio personalities]]\n[[Category:ESPN people]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:College football announcers]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Montgomery County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Scott Van Pelt \n| image = Scott Van Pelt.jpg\n| caption = Van Pelt at [[Stanford Stadium]] in 2013\n| birthname =\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = \n| height = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| education = [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]]\n| occupation = [[Sports commentator|Sportscaster]] \n| years_active = 1990\u2013present\n| alias = \n| title = \n| family =\n| spouse = Stephanie (m. 2011)\n| children = 2\n| relatives = \n| religion = \n| credits = Appeared on first episode of BVT ''[[SportsCenter]]'' (2001&ndash;present)<br />''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' (2009&ndash;2015, previously known as ''The Scott Van Pelt Show'') \n| agent = \n| salary = \n| URL = \n}}\n'''Scott Van Pelt''' is an American [[Sports commentator|sportscaster]] and sports [[talk show]] host. He co-anchored the 11 p.m. edition of ''[[SportsCenter]]'' on [[ESPN]], served as the co-host of ''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' alongside [[Ryen Russillo]] on [[ESPN Radio]], and hosts various [[golf]] events for the network. In June 2015, Van Pelt left his radio show to become a solo anchor for a midnight edition of ''SportsCenter''.\n\n==Early life==\nScott Van Pelt was born in [[Brookeville, Maryland]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/scott-van-pelt/bio/215846|title= Scott Van Pelt|publisher= TV Guide |accessdate= September 29, 2012}}</ref> and grew up in the [[Washington, D.C.]], area. He attended Flower Valley Elementary School in [[Rockville, Maryland]]. He graduated from [[Sherwood High School (Maryland)|Sherwood High School]] in [[Sandy Spring, Maryland]], and from the [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] in 1988 where he studied radio/television and film. He is a member of the [[Pi Kappa Alpha]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scott Van Pelt |url=http://www.espnmediazone3.com/us/2009/11/pelt_van_scott/ |date=November 17, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Mediazone |accessdate=October 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907111744/http://www.espnmediazone3.com/us/2009/11/pelt_van_scott/ |archivedate=September 7, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nScott Van Pelt began his career in sportscasting at [[WTTG-TV]], a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|FOX]] affiliate in [[Washington, D.C.]] in 1990 and then moved on to the [[Golf Channel]], where he worked from 1995 to 2000 as a studio host for some of the network's signature programs. He left the channel in 2001 to join [[ESPN]], where he serves as a presenter for ''[[SportsCenter]]'' and is one of the network's top [[golf]] correspondents, covering major tournaments such as the [[Masters Tournament]]. After acquiring the cable rights to the tournament, Van Pelt also appeared on ESPN's coverage of [[The Open Championship]]. He also is a prominent personality for [[ESPN Radio]], where he was the co-host of ''Tirico and Van Pelt'' alongside [[Mike Tirico]] before the program was canceled and replaced with Van Pelt's own three-hour program, ''The Scott Van Pelt Show'', in 2009. The show was renamed ''[[SVP & Russillo]]'' in October 2012. He is a studio presenter for the [[ESPN|ESPN Network's]] Friday night College Football on ESPN.\n\nVan Pelt has also appeared as a commentator in golf video games, alongside [[Kelly Tilghman]] on [[EA Sports]]' ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 10]]'' and ''[[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 11]]''<ref>{{cite web | title=Van Pelt's Tiger Woods PGA Tour 10 Voice Over Session | url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=3957568 | date=March 6, 2009}}</ref> and in a comedic turn in ''[[Aqua Teen Hunger Force Zombie Ninja Pro-Am]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gamesradar.com/ps2/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am/review/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am/a-20071108103544418012/g-20070716173729690035/p-1 | title=Aqua Teen Hunger Force: Zombie Ninja Pro-Am review | website=GamesRadar | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"gamespot\">{{cite web | url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/aqua-teen-hunger-force-zombie-ninja-pro-am-review/1900-6182650/ | title=Aqua Teen Hunger Force Zombie Ninja Pro-Am Review | website=GameSpot | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Van Pelt made the decision to stay with ESPN.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.shermanreport.com/qa-with-scott-van-pelt-looking-back-at-decision-to-stay-at-espn-radio-show-remains-key-component/ | title=Q/A with Scott Van Pelt: Looking back at decision to stay at ESPN; Radio show remains key component | first=Ed | last=Sherman | date=January 27, 2014 | publisher=EdShermanReport.com}}</ref> In May 2015, the network announced Van Pelt would leave the radio show SVP & Russillo to become a solo anchor for a midnight-edition of ''SportsCenter'', which began in late summer 2015. The midnight show covers sports events from the day, but includes additional commentary from Van Pelt and some popular elements from the radio show.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2015/05/scott-van-pelt-signs-extension-espn-will-take-midnight-et-sportscenter-solo-anchor/ | title = Scott Van Pelt Signs Extension with ESPN; Will Take Over Midnight (ET) SportsCenter as Solo Anchor | last = Livia Coelho | first = Ana | date = May 11, 2015 | work = ESPN MediaZone | access-date = May 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVan Pelt's family includes Lorenzo (grandfather)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/notthefakesvp/status/87911903053086721|title=Two Happy birthdays today: USA and my late grandpa Lorenzo from Italy via Brooklyn. I love and honor 'em both. The American dream is real|first=Scott Van|last=Pelt|date=July 4, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref> Cathie Mathis and Sam (parents).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.google.com/search?q=scott+van+pelt's+dad&oq=scott+van+pelt's+dad&aqs=chrome..69i57j0l3.4260j0j7&sourceid=chrome&es_sm=93&ie=UTF-8#q=scott+van+pelt+parents&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAOPgE-LUz9U3MKo0qihWQjC1JLOTrfQLUvMLclKBVFFxfp5VQWJRal5JMQA4wRBFMwAAAA | title=scott van pelt's dad - Google Search | website=www.google.com | accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nVan Pelt married Stephanie in 2011 and he has two children. His daughter Lila Catherine was born in 2012 and his son Sam was born in 2016. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://playerswiki.com/scott-van-pelt | title=Scott Van Pelt Biography | website=PlayersWiki.com | accessdate=November 12, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGrowing up in Maryland and graduating from College Park, Van Pelt is a fan of the [[Maryland Terrapins]], [[Washington Redskins]], [[Washington Capitals]], [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Washington Wizards|and Washington Wizards]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://espnmediazone.com/us/bios/pelt_van_scott/ ESPN bio]\n*{{Twitter}}\n*{{IMDb name|1207766}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131002120649/http://sd.pikes.org/309/sd309d.html Interview with Justin Buck and George Miller (\u03c0Ka Members)]\n\n{{ESPN}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Pelt, Scott}}\n[[Category:American television sports announcers]]\n[[Category:American sports radio personalities]]\n[[Category:ESPN people]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:College football announcers]]\n[[Category:University of Maryland, College Park alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Montgomery County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6000:101d:20f7:e9ff:a724:24ae:be74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCareer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Van_Pelt"}
{"title_page": "More Stuff", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = More Stuff\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Stuff (band)|Stuff]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1977\n| recorded   = 1976\u20131977\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Media Sound, New York City\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[funk]], [[jazz fusion]], [[soul music]], [[disco]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer   = Stuff, [[Van McCoy]], Charles Kipps\n| prev_title = [[Stuff (Stuff album)|Stuff]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = Stuff It\n| next_year  = 1978\n}}\n\n'''''More Stuff''''' is the title of the second full-length studio release by the group [[Stuff (band)|Stuff]].  It was released in 1977, a year after their debut, on Warner Bros. Records.  For the recordings, the group teamed up with Charles Kipps and Van McCoy, who by then had a disco hit with a song called \"[[The Hustle (song)|The Hustle]]\".  The band also covers the [[Stevie Wonder]] song \"[[As (song)|As]]\", which appeared on his ''[[Songs in the Key of Life]]'' disc from the same year.  ''More Stuff'', like its predecessor, attained gold status in the U.S.\n\n==Track Listing<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stuff-More-Stuff/release/1099535 Track Listing at discogs]</ref>==\n#\"This One's for You\" ([[Richard Tee]]) 5:07\n#\"And Here You Are\" (Tee, Gordon Edwards) 4:59\n#\"Subway ([[Cornell Dupree]]) 3:22\n#\"Love of Mine\" (Edwards) 4:05\n#\"Honey Coral Rock\" ([[Eric Gale]]) 5:09\n#\"Sometimes Bubba Gets Down\" (Chris Parker) 3:36\n#\"As\" ([[Stevie Wonder]]) 3:23\n#\"Need Somebody\" (Tee, Edwards) 6:30\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Stuff===\n*[[Richard Tee]] - Keyboards\n*[[Eric Gale]], [[Cornell Dupree]] - Guitars\n*[[Gordon Edwards (musician)|Gordon Edwards]] - Bass, Percussion\n*[[Steve Gadd]], [[Chris Parker (musician)|Chris Parker]] - Drums, Percussion\n\n===Additional Personnel===\n*[[Gene Orloff]] - Violin on \"And Here You Are\"\n\n==Production<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stuff-More-Stuff/release/1574478 Production information at discogs]</ref>==\n*Arranged by Stuff\n*Produced by Stuff, Van McCoy & Charles Kipps\n*Recorded & Mixed by Alan Varner & Alec Head; assisted by Don Berman & Ramona Janquitto\n*Track 1 published by Bloody Music Inc.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=1574478 Publishing information at discogs; scroll to see publishing]</ref>  Tracks 2 & 8 published by Yangor Music Inc./Bloody Music Inc.  Track 3 published by Corerm Music Inc.  Track 4 published by Yangor Music Inc.  Track 5 published by Gale Pyramid Music Inc.  Track 6 published by M'Bubba Music Inc.  Track 7 published by Jobete Music Inc./Black Bull Music Inc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1977 albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = More Stuff\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Stuff (band)|Stuff]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1977\n| recorded   = 1976\u20131977\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Media Sound, New York City\n| genre      = [[Jazz]], [[Funk]], [[Jazz Fusion]], [[Soul Music]], [[Disco]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer   = Stuff, [[Van McCoy]], Charles Kipps\n| prev_title = [[Stuff (Stuff album)|Stuff]]\n| prev_year  = 1976\n| next_title = Stuff It\n| next_year  = 1978\n}}\n\n'''''More Stuff''''' is the title of the second full-length studio release by the group [[Stuff (band)|Stuff]].  It was released in 1977, a year after their debut, on Warner Bros. Records.  For the recordings, the group teamed up with Charles Kipps and Van McCoy, who by then had a disco hit with a song called \"[[The Hustle (song)|The Hustle]]\".  The band also covers the [[Stevie Wonder]] song \"[[As (song)|As]]\", which appeared on his ''[[Songs in the Key of Life]]'' disc from the same year.  ''More Stuff'', like its predecessor, attained gold status in the U.S.\n\n==Track Listing<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stuff-More-Stuff/release/1099535 Track Listing at discogs]</ref>==\n#\"This One's for You\" ([[Richard Tee]]) 5:07\n#\"And Here You Are\" (Tee, Gordon Edwards) 4:59\n#\"Subway ([[Cornell Dupree]]) 3:22\n#\"Love of Mine\" (Edwards) 4:05\n#\"Honey Coral Rock\" ([[Eric Gale]]) 5:09\n#\"Sometimes Bubba Gets Down\" (Chris Parker) 3:36\n#\"As\" ([[Stevie Wonder]]) 3:23\n#\"Need Somebody\" (Tee, Edwards) 6:30\n\n==Personnel==\n\n===Stuff===\n*[[Richard Tee]] - Keyboards\n*[[Eric Gale]], [[Cornell Dupree]] - Guitars\n*[[Gordon Edwards (musician)|Gordon Edwards]] - Bass, Percussion\n*[[Steve Gadd]], [[Chris Parker (musician)|Chris Parker]] - Drums, Percussion\n\n===Additional Personnel===\n*[[Gene Orloff]] - Violin on \"And Here You Are\"\n\n==Production<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stuff-More-Stuff/release/1574478 Production information at discogs]</ref>==\n*Arranged by Stuff\n*Produced by Stuff, Van McCoy & Charles Kipps\n*Recorded & Mixed by Alan Varner & Alec Head; assisted by Don Berman & Ramona Janquitto\n*Track 1 published by Bloody Music Inc.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/viewimages?release=1574478 Publishing information at discogs; scroll to see publishing]</ref>  Tracks 2 & 8 published by Yangor Music Inc./Bloody Music Inc.  Track 3 published by Corerm Music Inc.  Track 4 published by Yangor Music Inc.  Track 5 published by Gale Pyramid Music Inc.  Track 6 published by M'Bubba Music Inc.  Track 7 published by Jobete Music Inc./Black Bull Music Inc.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1977 albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "lower case", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/More_Stuff"}
